In J.R.R. Tolkien's revered Lord of the Rings series, power is a pivotal element that permeates the narrative, driving the plot and shaping the characters' trajectories. The struggle for power forms the underlying fabric of Middle-earth, to which all other conflicts are intricately connected.

On one hand, there is the malevolent force of Sauron's dark lordship, whose unquenchable thirst for domination seeks to enslave all peoples and extinguish freedom. His power is exemplified by the Nazgûl and the One Ring – symbols of oppression and bondage that spread fear and despair throughout the realm. In contrast, soreside, of the virtuous yet fragile societies of Elves, Dwarf realms under fire, Gandalf symbolizes wisdom wieldpowerwisely, guiding Fellowship members through tumult while avoiding exploitation or tyranny.
